I&#39;ve often wondered abut this.  It seems others have often gotten EVP 
where I didn&#39;t, at the same time and place.

I got a LOT of them at the former Manteno State Mental Hospital (Illinois) 
last year though.  I got the same ones on both a pocket DVR and a 
camcorder. Most were Class B EVP because they were barely perceptible. 
Being a radio amateur who has spent hundreds of hours digging weak voices 
out of the noise helps to hear them, though. I did get a few Class A&#39;s.

Some of the things I heard were like these.  When I write &quot;questioner&quot; I 
mean someone in the group who asked the question.  When I write &quot;EVP&quot; I 
mean the response, which was not from anyone in the group.

Questioner: &quot;Are there other spirits here with you?&quot; / EVP: &quot;You bet&quot; 
(male voice, slightly speeded up)

Questioner: &quot;Are you happy?&quot; / EVP: &quot;Course I&#39;m haaaapeeee&quot; (long 
drawn-out male voice, almost slowed down)

Questioner: Do you know what year it is?&quot; / EVP: &quot;1996&quot; (female voice, 
normal speed, very dim. The year was in fact 2006).

Questioner: &quot;Do you like it here?&quot; / EVP: &quot;Leave this building!&quot; (normal 
male voice but quite dim and almost in noise)

Two group members chatting, suddenly a very speeded up word thrown in / 
EVP: &quot;Fantastic&quot;. (I slowed it to half-speed with Audacity, then it 
sounded like a normal male voice with a slight accent - Italian?)

Group member commenting on shadow figure seen in adjacent part of building 
through window: &quot;... I don&#39;t think it&#39;s a person, at least living.&quot; / EVP: 
&quot;It&#39;s Harold Wing&quot;.  Group member &quot;I can still see it moving&quot; / EVP: &quot;It&#39;s 
Harold Wing&quot;.  Group member makes another comment / EVP &quot;It&#39;s Harold.&quot; 
(This was a Class A EVP, sounding like a very loud whisper or hoarse male 
voice).

The Manteno State Mental Hospital was closed in 1985.  There&#39;s a lot of 
info here: http://www.mantenostatehospital.com

The building we were in was the last remaining building of the original 
hospital still standing that hasn&#39;t been renovated or destroyed - the 
Morgan Building.  A researcher found out that there was a patient there in 
1936 named Arnold Wing who died of malaria or typhoid.

Verrry interesting stuff!

Zack

